y</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0002-4141-3747</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG001898%2F1"><gtr:id>BC17A0E3-FFA7-4EBB-992B-9207E564CC7A</gtr:id><gtr:title>A multilevel approach to understanding the aetiology of work-related health and well-being: Linking individual and organisational factors</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G001898/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>A large body of research has shown that employee health and well-being is determined by a multitude of work and organisational characteristics. However, findings have often been inconsistent, for two main reasons:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>First, the majority of research has focused on individual-level variables (eg job demands, relationships at work, social support, coping resources) and has largely ignored the impact of higher-level organisational characteristics (eg policies and practices, leadership, organisational change). 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Second, although the study of work-related health is concerned with the individual within the wider organisation, research methodology has typically used single-level approaches. Inconsistent findings can have important implications for the management of work-related health.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The aim of this project is to understand which and in what way elements of the wider organisational context influence employee work-related health, using an appropriate methodology. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>It takes a multilevel approach by looking at the impact of both individual and organisational level characteristics simultaneously. In order to establish causal links, it also assesses relationships at multiple points in time. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The findings of the project will help to extend current theory on the determinants of work-related health. They will also help to develop the necessary knowledge and skills for managing work-related health in a successful and sustainable way.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>264777</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>Fit for Work</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:description>Collaboration with the Leicester Fit for Work Team</gtr:description><gtr:id>5603ADA9-6278-461E-A8E9-46F621DB519A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Inclusion of the Workplace Climate Measure in the Health Needs Assessment Questionnaire</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>5469c36e8a7808.84578977-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>See above. Inclusion of the workplace climate measure in the Health Needs Assessment Questionnaire means that more organisations have the opportunity to use it and benefit from this new work.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>A short version of the measure of workplace climate that was developed as part of the ESRC Work and Well-being in Context project (2009-11) was included in the Health Needs Assessment Questionnaire developed by the Leicester Fit for Work team. This is available to its member organisations. Furthermore, the PI is in collaboration with the Fit for Work team providing assistance in administering and interpreting the climate measure, and in developing and implementing workplace interventions as a result of that.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector